}*[[[break]]]added at line 52: *lime {code 
*red To round off my temporary and tentative, probably ill-formed generalisation about how science is (descriptively) conducted: 

From above...Experimentalists interpret the hypotheses and design experiments to test them, and interpret the data from the experiments to (simply put) prove or disprove the hypothesis. 

If 'proven' the hypothesis adds to or consolidates the theory, if disproved (maybe unproved is better) the hypothesis is reformulated or rejected.

It may be in keeping with this (and Kuhn?) to say that, in some cases, the nature of the disproof of the hypothesis (e.g. anomalous data that recurs in repeated experiments) stimulates theoreticians to challenge the underlying theory of the paradigm and propose new hypotheses (even theories?) which is in effect the beginning of a paradigm shift.

I'd be keen to know how people think this fits, with Kuhn and/or how useful it is as a descriptive generalisation of what scientists do.

Hamish* 

