[[[break]]]added at line 40: *lime {code 
*red I agree that it's more efficient to target experiments at a theory (hypothesis), but Kuhn's stuff about paradigms (in the sense of disciplinary matrices) may be worth mentioning here.

I have a limited experience of what scientists actually do, but I think I agree with Greg.

I would say descriptively (of theoreticians and experimentalist - who can be, and often are, the same person) that theoreticians interpret the theories which underpin the paradigm and form hypotheses (i.e start asking the sorts of questions they're allowed to ask). Experimentalists interpret the hypotheses and design experiments to test them, and interpret the data from the experiments to (simply put) prove or disprove the hypothesis.

Because that all takes place within the paradigm (governed by the reigning theory) there's a lot of room for bias (note the multiple use of interpret in the above paragraph). Descriptively but very subjectively: I have been surprised by how many of my science-student colleagues seemed unaware of this and/or uncomprehending of it. I have also been surprised that, of those who understand and agree, many seem to think it was of little significance - doesn't affect the epistemic claims of science.

I'm not sure what to do about that bias, or whether, ultimately, anything can be done about it. I do think, normatively, that students of science should be taught more about 'the scientific method' from a philosophical point of view, if only to be more aware that there is neither a single 'scientific method' nor (to my knowledge) a simple generalisation that sums up how science should (normatively) be conducted.

Hamish* 
}*
