[[[break]]]changed line 18 from: *orange {code *red Jason pointed out that "there are many theories which explain current experimental data in this area". I would content that hypothesis is again more appropriate here than theory - feel free to disagree. Jason's slide also said (not that slides speak...) "For some reason they are called 'interpretations' of quantum mechanics - as if they were all part of the same theory. They all explain the data equally well." In my view time-symmetric/decoherence/many worlds etc, are competing hypotheses that have been formulated based on the same experimental data, in other words different intepretations of data from quantum mechanics. I think it might have been better to say 'they are all comparable in the extent to which they fail to fully explain the data'. This helps explain why I think they're better labelled as hypotheses. In my view there is no validly labelled theroy of quantum mechanics because the current hypotheses fail to fully explain the data and/or fail to cohere with accepted theory in overlapping fields and/or they are presently very difficult to falsify. So new hypotheses are needed, or new ways of testing hypotheses, or a re-interpretation of non-compatible, overlapping theories, before quantum mechanics can approach an explanation which qualifies as a theory.
