[[[break]]]added at line 10: *lime {code 
*red It may be mere semantic pedantry (or is no pedantry 'mere' in philosophy?), but I wonder whether hypothesis may be a more suitable term than theory in the above post...while the terms are often used interchangably it is my understanding that a 'theory' has a broader scope than hypothesis, with the latter fitting well in the above context and the former being more applicable to a unification of multiple, related, rigourously tested (attempted falsification if possible) hypotheses. I don't know that scientists test theories directly with observational data, they do so via the hypotheses that constitute the theory. This leads to a point which is relevant to our lecture on "interpretations" of quantum mechanics. 

Jason pointed out that "there are many theories which explain current experimental data in this area". I would content that hypothesis is again more appropriate here than theory - feel free to disagree. Jason's slide also said (not that slides speak...) "For some reason they are called 'interpretations' of quantum mechanics - as if they were all part of the same theory. They all explain the data equally well." In my view time-symmetric/decoherence/many worlds etc, are competing hypotheses that have been formulated based on the same experimental data, in other words different intepretations of data from quantum mechanics. I think it might have been better to say 'they are all comparable in the extent to which they fail to fully explain the data'. This helps explain why I think they're better labelled as hypotheses. In my view there is no validly labelled theroy of quantum mechanics because the current hypotheses fail to fully explain the data and/or fail to cohere with accepted theory in overlapping fields and/or they are presently very difficult to falsify. So new hypotheses are needed, or new ways of testing hypotheses, or a re-interpretation of non-compatible, overlapping theories, before quantum mechanics can approach an explanation which qualifies as a theory.


RE Lorenzo's Einstein quotes: I would like to think that scientists wouldn't be content to rest on their laurels, or on the laurels of the giants before them. I hope we aren't inclined to settle for "so loose and flimsy a description of nature". I think one of the most significant recurring themes in history of science is that every time scientists/philosophers thought they were approaching a comprehensive understanding of the world...they turned out to be wrong. It is possible that one day we will arrive at a TOE (theory of everything), I think. But I also think best-practice would be to continue to assume we haven't arrived there yet, even when we're inclined to think we have. Perhaps the most ardent proponents of the idea that we are nearing a TOE should take a lesson from Russell's chicken; next time we assume we have things right and act on those assumptions (subsequently discovered to be inductively derived falsehoods) we may just have our heads chopped off. Now, I don't have particular concerns about the upcoming experiments with CERN's LHC, however that may just be because I don't know enough about it, or the neccessary background to fully comprehend it. I just hope that misplaced confidence in the accuracy of scientific knowledge, and its technological applications, don't lead us down an unpleasant path.

Hamish*
}*
