[[[break]]]added at line 0: *lime {code Some one asked today why it was important that we review the different case studies of what scientists actually do and i wanted to venture an answer of my own. It especially relates to these examples of physics we've been looking it. I think these theories that are at the forefront of physics provide an especially vivid characterisation of what scientists actually do. 

I think in the examples of theoretical physics we've been looking at it is the easiest to see the real mechanism by which scientific knowledge expands. While it is a common view-point that scientists grow their theories by making lots of observations and then connecting the dots (Observations -> theory) I contented that in reality the opposite is going on. Real science starts with a theory (the creation of a theory is thus a vibrant and creative process) and then tries to falsify parts or all of that theory with empirical experience. If the theory is wrong they start again, if parts of it are wrong, they improve on their theory (Theory -> Observations -> Better theory, etc.). This is all Popper’s stuff and I'm sure we'll talk about this further on in the course so i won't waffle on too much here except to say that no where else can one find a better example of what i just described occurring in the real world than in the growth of quantum mechanics. A short read of the history of how all this stuff came about will demonstrate this I believe. 

A parting thought on all the stuff about Schrodinger's cat, i found a letter by Einstein to Popper, at the end of it Einstein says two inspiring things: 

Firstly, "An orthodox quantum theorist will say, of course, that there is no such thing as a complete description and that there can be only a statistical description of an aggregate of systems, rather than a description of one single system. But first of all, he ought to say so clearly; and secondly, i do not believe that we shall have to be satisfied for ever with so loose and flimsy a description of nature" (Almost brings a tear to my eye!)

And equally importantly "A method of description which, like the one now in use, is statistical in principle, can only be a passing phase, in my opinion"
Lorenzo
}*